History

From the beginning, Iroquois Capital Group has been a Nashville-based provider of financial services to early-stage and lower middle market companies. In 2006, Iroquois was founded to take over the management of a troubled institutional pharmacy company, which became our initial portfolio company. A large publicly held health care company later acquired this company, creating a favorable return for its investors.
Iroquois next founded the portfolio company REIT Investment Group (“RIG”), which provides shareholder and compliance services to over 300 private REITs, giving investors access to preferred stock in these REITs.
Through Iroquois Capital Advisors—our FINRA member broker-dealer—we offer highly selective alternative investments to high net worth individuals. An example of such an investment is Iroquois’ portfolio company, Covenant Surgical Partners (“CSP”), which acquires, owns and manages ambulatory surgery centers. In 2008, Iroquois and its investors provided CSP its initial seed funding. Over $200 million of additional capital for CSP’s growth has been provided through our network of high net worth individuals and institutions, along with Iroquois’ continued participation in each round of equity offerings.
In early 2011, Iroquois created its investment banking group to provide mergers and acquisitions advisory and private capital raising services for middle market companies.
Iroquois expanded its platform of specialty finance services and created Iroquois Financial Partners I, LP (“IFP I”), which provided credit support for loans made to early stage companies in need of capital, affording qualified investors the opportunity to invest in growth-stage companies. Investors in IFP I were given the ability to realize a return on an “under-utilized” asset–their personal credit. This is different than the typical committed capital arrangement.
In 2013, Iroquois created an additional alternative investment opportunity for qualified investors by merging IFP I into Iroquois Financial Partners II, L.P. (“IFP II”). IFP II provides qualified investors the same opportunities as IFP I but on a much larger scale.
Iroquois has a long and successful track record of providing debt and equity capital and offering investment banking services to middle market companies and providing alternative investments for our base of high net worth individuals and institutional investors.


